CHECK_TITLE: Check if there are CMK KMS keys not used.
DESCRIPTION: Check if there are CMK KMS keys not used.
RISK: Unused keys may increase service cost.
REMEDIATION_RECOMMENDATION_TEXT: Before deleting a customer master key (CMK), you might want to know how many cipher-texts were encrypted under that key.
COMPLIANCE: KISA-ISMS-P-2023-korean: 2.7.2, 2.10.1, 2.10.2 | C5-2025: OIS-08.02B, CRY-03.01B, CRY-05.02B, CRY-19.01B | KISA-ISMS-P-2023: 2.7.2, 2.10.1, 2.10.2 | ISO27001-2022: A.8.5, A.8.11, A.8.24 | CCC: CCC.KeyMgmt.CN02.AR01, CCC.KeyMgmt.CN04.AR01, CCC.Core.CN11.AR01, CCC.Core.CN11.AR02, CCC.Core.CN11.AR03, CCC.Core.CN11.AR04 | AWS-Well-Architected-Framework-Security-Pillar: SEC08-BP01

CHECK_TITLE: AWS KMS keys should not be deleted unintentionally
STATUS_EXTENDED: KMS CMK 85514e87-1879-48ad-90fb-526214380a57 is not scheduled for deletion.
DESCRIPTION: Ensure there is no customer keys scheduled for deletion.
RISK: KMS keys cannot be recovered once deleted, also, all the data under a KMS key is also permanently unrecoverable if the KMS key is deleted.
REMEDIATION_RECOMMENDATION_TEXT: Cancel the deletion before the end of the period unless you really want to delete that CMK, as it will no longer be usable.
COMPLIANCE: KISA-ISMS-P-2023-korean: 2.7.2, 2.9.2, 2.10.1 | C5-2025: OIS-08.02B, AM-07.02B, CRY-03.01B, CRY-05.02B, CRY-16.02B, CRY-19.01B | NIST-CSF-2.0: ra_1, ds_3 | AWS-Foundational-Security-Best-Practices: KMS.3 | PCI-4.0: 3.5.1.1.9, 3.5.1.3.17, 3.6.1.2.9, 3.6.1.3.9, 3.6.1.4.9, 3.6.1.9, 3.7.1.10, 3.7.2.9, 3.7.4.10, 3.7.6.9, 3.7.7.9, 4.2.1.1.22 | KISA-ISMS-P-2023: 2.7.2, 2.9.2, 2.10.1 | ISO27001-2022: A.8.11, A.8.24 | CCC: CCC.KeyMgmt.CN01.AR01, CCC.KeyMgmt.CN02.AR01, CCC.KeyMgmt.CN04.AR01, CCC.ObjStor.CN01.AR02, CCC.ObjStor.CN01.AR03, CCC.ObjStor.CN01.AR04, CCC.ObjStor.CN05.AR04, CCC.Core.CN11.AR01, CCC.Core.CN11.AR02, CCC.Core.CN11.AR03, CCC.Core.CN11.AR04

CHECK_TITLE: AWS KMS customer managed keys should not be multi-Region
STATUS_EXTENDED: KMS CMK 85514e87-1879-48ad-90fb-526214380a57 is a single-region key.
DESCRIPTION: Ensure that AWS KMS customer managed keys (CMKs) are not multi-region to maintain strict data control and compliance with security best practices.
RISK: Multi-region KMS keys can increase the risk of unauthorized access and data exposure, as managing access controls and auditing across multiple regions becomes more complex. This expanded attack surface may lead to compliance violations and data breaches.
REMEDIATION_RECOMMENDATION_TEXT: Identify and replace multi-region keys with single-region KMS keys to enhance security and access control.
COMPLIANCE: C5-2025: OIS-08.02B, PS-02.01B, PS-02.01AS, PS-02.02AS, CRY-03.01B, CRY-05.02B, CRY-10.01B, CRY-19.01B, PSS-12.02AC | NIST-CSF-2.0: ra_1 | ISO27001-2022: A.8.11, A.8.24 | CCC: CCC.KeyMgmt.CN02.AR01, CCC.KeyMgmt.CN04.AR01, CCC.ObjStor.CN01.AR04, CCC.Core.CN11.AR01, CCC.Core.CN11.AR02, CCC.Core.CN11.AR03, CCC.Core.CN11.AR04, CCC.Core.CN11.AR05
NOTES: Multi-region keys should be used only when absolutely necessary, such as for cross-region disaster recovery, and should be carefully managed with strict access controls.

CHECK_TITLE: Ensure rotation for customer created KMS CMKs is enabled.
STATUS_EXTENDED: KMS CMK 85514e87-1879-48ad-90fb-526214380a57 has automatic rotation disabled.
DESCRIPTION: Ensure rotation for customer created KMS CMKs is enabled.
RISK: Cryptographic best practices discourage extensive reuse of encryption keys. Consequently, Customer Master Keys (CMKs) should be rotated to prevent usage of compromised keys.
REMEDIATION_RECOMMENDATION_TEXT: For every KMS Customer Master Keys (CMKs), ensure that Rotate this key every year is enabled.
COMPLIANCE: KISA-ISMS-P-2023-korean: 2.7.2, 2.10.1, 2.10.2 | C5-2025: OIS-08.02B, CRY-05.02B, CRY-06.01B, CRY-07.01B, CRY-09.02B, CRY-19.01B | NIS2: 11.6.2.c | AWS-Foundational-Security-Best-Practices: KMS.4 | HIPAA: 164_312_a_2_iv | PCI-4.0: 3.7.4.5, 3.7.5.2 | CIS-1.5: 3.8 | ProwlerThreatScore-1.0: 3.2.1 | NIST-800-53-Revision-5: cm_6_a, cm_9_b, sa_9_6, sc_12, sc_12_2, sc_12_6 | ENS-RD2022: op.exp.10.aws.cmk.3 | SOC2: pi_1_5 | FedRamp-Moderate-Revision-4: sc-12 | KISA-ISMS-P-2023: 2.7.2, 2.10.1, 2.10.2 | FedRAMP-Low-Revision-4: sc-12 | RBI-Cyber-Security-Framework: annex_i_1_3 | CIS-3.0: 3.6 | CIS-1.4: 3.8 | CIS-4.0.1: 3.6 | NIST-800-53-Revision-4: sc_12 | CISA: your-systems-3 | CIS-2.0: 3.8 | GDPR: article_25, article_30 | FedRAMP-20x-KSI-Low-25.05C: ksi-svc | GxP-21-CFR-Part-11: 11.30 | ISO27001-2022: A.8.5, A.8.11, A.8.24 | CCC: CCC.KeyMgmt.CN02.AR01, CCC.KeyMgmt.CN03.AR01, CCC.KeyMgmt.CN04.AR01, CCC.Core.CN11.AR01, CCC.Core.CN11.AR02, CCC.Core.CN11.AR03, CCC.Core.CN11.AR04, CCC.Core.CN11.AR05, CCC.Core.CN11.AR06 | CIS-5.0: 3.6 | AWS-Well-Architected-Framework-Security-Pillar: SEC02-BP05

STATUS_EXTENDED: KMS key 85514e87-1879-48ad-90fb-526214380a57 is not exposed to Public.
RISK: Exposed KMS Keys or wide policy permissions my leave data unprotected.
REMEDIATION_RECOMMENDATION_TEXT: To determine the full extent of who or what currently has access to a customer master key (CMK) in AWS KMS, you must examine the CMK key policy, all grants that apply to the CMK and potentially all AWS Identity and Access Management (IAM) policies. You might do this to determine the scope of potential usage of a CMK.
